Want to know the types of waste?

Biodegradable is the property of a material or product that can be broken down naturally by microorganisms such as bacteria or fungi into simpler substances such as water, carbon dioxide, and biomass. This decomposition process usually occurs in a natural environment or under certain conditions such as composting. biodegradable materials are a more environmentally friendly alternative

Non-biodegradable refers to materials or substances that cannot be broken down by natural microorganisms such as bacteria or fungi. This means that the material will not break down and decompose into basic harmless materials in the environment within a reasonable period of time. As a result, non-biodegradable materials can remain in the environment for years or even centuries, causing pollution and other environmental problems.

It then explores emerging technological solutions to overcome these challenges, including computer vision-based systems, artificial intelligence (AI) algorithms, and machine learning (ML) techniques.

Natural biodegradable materials are organic materials made from natural materials such as wood fiber, paper, and vegetables. These materials are biodegradable and can be decomposed by microorganisms in nature in a relatively short period of time.

Synthetic biodegradable materials are man-made materials made from synthetic chemicals, such as poly lactate (PLA) or polyhydroxy alkanoate (PHA). These materials are designed to biodegrade under certain environmental conditions and can be broken down by microorganisms such as bacteria and fungi.

Oxodegradable materials are synthetic materials that contain chemicals that make them break down easily when exposed to sunlight or heat. However, they can still leave behind small particles that are difficult to break down and harmful to the environment.

Photodegradable materials are synthetic materials that break down through exposure to ultraviolet light or light. However, they can still leave behind small particles that are difficult to break down and harmful to the environment.

Programmed biodegradable materials are synthetic materials that have been designed to break down under controlled environmental conditions, such as under compostable conditions or within a sewage treatment plant.

This type of waste is waste or waste that is soft or flexible and easy to shape. For example, plastic waste, styrofoam, fast food wrappers. In addition, there are also liquid ones, such as used detergent water, soap water, cooking oil and so on.

This type of waste is easily destroyed because it contains strong materials. This waste can only be destroyed by certain destruction methods, such as heating or burning. The examples are broken glass, ceramics, rusty nails, and used cans.
